\begin_layout Title
Project 2: Polarization of Light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
September 27th, 2017
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Gianfranco Grillo
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We present the results of a series of five experiments designed to investigate
 different aspects of the polarization of light.
 In the first experiment, we perform a verification of Malus's Law and find
 the extinction ratio between two identical polarizers.
 Our results are consistent with Malus's Law, and we calculate the extinction
 ratio as x, which is close to the nominal value.
 The second experiment measures the index of refraction 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of a glass prism by finding its Brewster's angle, obtaining a value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1.46\pm0.05$
\end_inset

.
 In the third experiment, we measure the reflectance coefficient of a blackened
 flat in two different ways, one by fitting a curve according to Fresnel's
 equations, and another by finding the azimuthal angle.
 We find general agreement between the two methods.
 In the fourth experiment, we qualitatively examine the polarization of
 light by scattering.
 Finally, we study the effects of birefringent materials on incident light,
 and determine the phase shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 introduced by an overhead transparency on linearly polarized light.
 We find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=70\pm10^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to classical electromagnetism, light consists in electromagnetic
 waves of a particular frequency that propagate in a direction perpendicular
 to the oscillations of the electric field and the magnetic field.
 As long as they are perpendicular with respect to each other and the direction
 of propagation, the electric and magnetic fields can oscillate in an arbitrary
 orientation.
 The geometrical characteristics of this orientation are known as the wave's
 polarization.
 Monochromatic polarized light traveling in an arbitrarily defined z-direction
 can be described in a straightforward manner in terms of the amplitudes
 of the x- and y-components of their electric fields, as well as the phase
 difference between them.
 In this project, we use a monochromatic laser beam of wavelength 632.8 nm
 and perform a series of measurements that can be successfully modeled under
 this framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We perform the data analysis using Python and the associated library SciPy
 ([1]) and Uncertainty package ([2]).
\end_layout

