\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electromagnetic waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wave equations in vacuum for the electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 and the magnetic field 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{B}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
follow from Maxwell's equations and are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nabla^{2}\vec{E} & = & \epsilon_{0}\mu_{0}\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{E}}{\partial t^{2}}\\
\nabla^{2}\vec{B} & = & \epsilon_{0}\mu_{0}\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{B}}{\partial t^{2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

 are the permittivity and permeability of free space, respectively.
 Faraday's Law states that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\nabla}\times\vec{E}=-\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the derivation in [3], we can consider the case of a monochromatic
 plane wave of linear polarization moving in the z-direction, where the
 electric and magnetic fields are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tilde{E} & = & \tilde{E}_{0}e^{i(kz-\omega t)}\\
\tilde{B} & = & \tilde{B}_{0}e^{i(kz-\omega t)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gauss's Law for electric and magnetic fields in free space requires that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\nabla}\cdot\vec{B}=\vec{\nabla}\cdot\vec{E}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which implies that both fields are transverse to the direction of propagation
 of the wave, since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\vec{E}_{0})_{z}=(\vec{B}_{0})_{z}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, equation (3) forces the electric and magnetic fields to be perpendicul
ar to each other, since (3) requires that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-k(\tilde{E}_{0})_{y}=\omega(\tilde{B}_{0})_{x},\,k(\tilde{E}_{0})_{x}=\omega(\tilde{B}_{0})_{y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can also be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{B}_{0}=\frac{k}{\omega}(\hat{z}\times\tilde{E}_{0})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In linear, non-absorbing media with no free charge or free current, this
 relationship also holds, since equation (6) is still true, and the only
 change in the other equations is that the constants in Faraday's law change
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{o}$
\end_inset

 to the corresponding permittivity and permeability of the specific medium
 in question, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the velocity of the wave changes, but not their transverse quality
 or the characteristic that the electric and magnetic fields are perpendicular
 to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polarization by a plastic film
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the properties that describes electromagnetic waves is their polarization
, which is related to the geometrical orientation of their electric fields.
 The orientation of the electric field of an electromagnetic wave traveling
 in the +z-direction can be described in terms of the relationships between
 the amplitudes and phases of the electric field's x- and y-components.
 We say that light is linearly polarized when one of the components of the
 electric field is equal to zero, and thus the electric field oscillates
 in only one axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear polarization can be achieved by means of a thin plastic film made
 of polymer chains covered with iodine.
 Iodine is a light absorbing element, and the plastic film is manufactured
 in such a way that the polymer chains align in a particular direction.
 Randomly polarized light incident in such a film becomes linearly polarized,
 as only the component of the electric field perpendicular to the direction
 of the film's polymer chains is transmitted by the film.
 The iodine covering the polymer chains preferentially absorbs the light
 incident parallel to it, as its electrons are able to oscillate freely
 along that axis.
 The radiation emitted due to the oscillations of these electrons is 
\begin_inset Formula $180^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 out of phase with respect to the incident radiation, which means that very
 little light gets transmitted with its field oscillating in that direction.
 The only direction in which the electrons cannot oscillate at all is perpendicu
lar to the direction of the polymer chains, so the component of the electric
 field along this axis is the only one that is transmitted by the film.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Malus's Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An optical system composed of two linear polarizers will transmit a certain
 amount of light that depends on the relative orientations of the axes of
 the two constituent polarizers.
 The precise relationship between the transmitted intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and the angle between the axes of the polarizers 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is known as Malus's Law, and is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I(\theta)=I_{0}\cos^{2}\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the intensity of the light emerging from the first polarizer.
 The obvious consequences of this relationship is that maximum transmission
 occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, that is, when the two polarizer axes are aligned with each other, whereas
 minimum transmission occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to the configuration in which the axes of transmission
 of both polarizers are perpendicular to each other.
 This law should hold exactly for the case of two ideal polarizers which
 transmit all the light incident along their transmission axis and block
 all other light.
 In practice, however, some of the light that is not parallel to the transmissio
n axis is allowed to go through, and some of the light parallel to the transmiss
ion axis is blocked.
 A measure of deviation from ideal is the extinction ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{e}$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{e}=\frac{I_{min}}{I_{max}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{min}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{max}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the minimum intensity and maximum intensities emerging from
 the system, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fresnel's equations and Brewster's angle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electric field of an electromagnetic wave incident on a surface can
 be conveniently expressed in terms of its components parallel (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

) and perpendicular (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) to the plane of incidence.
 The Fresnel equations relate the magnitude of the reflected fields to that
 of the incident fields for each of the components, and are given in [4]
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{\parallel}=\frac{E_{\parallel_{r}}}{E_{\parallel_{i}}} & = & \frac{\tan(\theta_{i}-\theta_{t})}{\tan(\theta_{i}+\theta_{t})}\\
r_{\perp}=\frac{E_{\perp_{r}}}{E_{\perp_{i}}} & = & -\frac{\sin(\theta_{i}-\theta_{t})}{\sin(\theta_{i}+\theta_{t})}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These ratios are also known as the reflection coefficients.
 The incident wave becomes completely polarized when 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 vanishes, which occurs when its denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan(\theta_{i}+\theta_{t})\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, that is, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}+\theta_{t}=90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 Snell's Law indicates that for an air/dielectric interface, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
n\sin\theta_{t} & =\sin\theta_{i}=\sin(90^{\circ}-\theta_{t})=\cos\theta_{t}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}$
\end_inset

 gives the transmission angle that results in completely polarized light,
 also known as Brewster's angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{b}$
\end_inset

, in honor of Sir David Brewster, who first discovered it in 1815.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{b}=\arctan(n)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will calculate the refractive index of a glass prism in experiment 2
 by means of this equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using trigonometric identities and Snell's Law, it is possible to rewrite
 (12) and (13) strictly in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
r_{\parallel} & = & \frac{n^{2}\cos\theta_{i}-\sqrt{n^{2}-\sin^{2}\theta_{i}}}{n^{2}\cos\theta_{i}+\sqrt{n^{2}-\sin^{2}\theta_{i}}}\\
r_{\perp} & = & \frac{\cos\theta_{i}-\sqrt{n^{2}-\sin^{2}\theta_{i}}}{\cos\theta_{i}+\sqrt{n^{2}-\sin^{2}\theta_{i}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiment 3 of this project will verify these equations by comparing the
 incident intensities of light alternatively polarized along the plane of
 incidence and perpendicular to the plane of incidence to the reflected
 intensities, as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The ratio between the reflected intensity and the incident intensity correspond
s to the square of the ratio of the reflected electric field and the incident
 electric field.
 That is
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\parallel}=r_{\parallel}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\perp}=r_{\perp}^{2}$
\end_inset

, so our measurements should be described by the square of equations (16)
 and (17).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polarization and scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Randomly polarized light incident on a group of molecules causes the molecules
 to start oscillating parallel to the direction of the light's electric
 field's oscillations.
 Because the light is unpolarized, the direction of oscillation will change
 with time in a practically random way, but it will always be perpendicular
 to the direction of the light's propagation.
 This means that molecules will oscillate perpendicularly to the direction
 of propagation.
 As explained in section 2.2, as the molecules oscillate, they reradiate
 light in all directions except for that of their axis of oscillation, and
 the reradiated light will be out of phase with respect to the incident
 light, which will result in the light becoming polarized.
 In practice, this means that the reradiated light emerging from a direction
 normal to that of the propagation of the incident light beam will be completely
 linearly polarized, and the reradiated light emerging in the same direction
 of the incident beam will emerge randomly polarized.
 A more detailed explanation of this phenomenon can be found in [5].
 The light reradiated in directions that are neither normal nor perpendicular
 to the direction of propagation will be partially polarized.
 Experiment 4 qualitatively verifies these concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Birefringence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Birefringence corresponds to the phenomenon in which the components of a
 beam's electric field undergo a relative phase shift as they pass through
 a material, because not all the beam's light is able to travel at the same
 speed within the material.
 Depending on the geometrical orientation of the beam's constituent electric
 fields, the velocity at which parts of the beam travel is different from
 that of other parts, because a birefringent material has more than one
 refractive index.
 In experiment 5, we will examine the properties of a uniaxial birefringent
 material, for which one of its axes has a different refractive index than
 the other two.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first setup in that experiment will involve placing a quarter wave plate
 in between two polarizers, with respect to the orientation of a laser beam's
 propagation.
 Linearly polarized light passing through a quarter wave plate becomes circularl
y polarized because the quarter wave plate introduces a phase shift of 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 between the x- and y-components of the incident electric field.
 Crossing the first polarizer with the second polarizer (which in this context
 is referred to as an analyzer), and introducing the quarter wave plate
 in between them with its fast axis at an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with respect to the horizontal axis of the system, and rotating the system
 in such a way that the transmission axis of the first polarizer points
 in the y-direction, implies that the transmitted components of the electric
 field are proportional to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
E_{t_{x}}\\
E_{t_{y}}
\end{array}\right] & \propto & e^{-\frac{i\pi}{4}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\cos^{2}\theta+i\sin^{2}\theta & (1-i)\sin\theta\cos\theta\\
(1-i)\sin\theta\cos\theta & \sin^{2}\theta+i\cos^{2}\theta
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1
\end{array}\right]\\
 & \propto & e^{-\frac{i\pi}{4}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
(1-i)\sin\theta\cos\theta\\
\sin^{2}\theta+i\cos^{2}\theta
\end{array}\right]\\
 & \propto & e^{\frac{-i\pi}{4}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
(1-i)\cos\theta\sin\theta\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum transmitted intensity will occur when the squared magnitude
 of the vector in (19) is maximum, that is, at the maximum of the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(\theta)=2\cos^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=-45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=135^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting either of these angles into the vector in (19), and multiplying
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\frac{i\pi}{4}}$
\end_inset

, gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
E_{t_{x}}\\
E_{t_{y}}
\end{array}\right]\propto\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
i\\
1
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus the light emerging from the quarter wave plate is circularly polarized.
 If we now rotate the analyzer such that its transmission axis forms and
 angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with the horizontal axis of the optical system, (22) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
E_{t_{x}}\\
E_{t_{y}}
\end{array}\right] & \propto & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\cos^{2}\phi & \sin\phi\cos\phi\\
\sin\phi\cos\phi & \sin^{2}\phi
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
i\\
1
\end{array}\right]\\
 & \propto & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
i\cos^{2}\phi+\sin\phi\cos\phi\\
i\sin\phi\cos\phi+\sin^{2}\phi
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The squared magnitude of the vector in (24) is a constant, which implies
 that rotating the analyzer should have no effect on the intensity of the
 transmitted light.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second setup of the experiment is designed in order to find the phase
 shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 due to an overhead transparency.
 The new setup makes the beam pass through a vertical linear polarizer,
 the overhead transparency with its fast axis set at an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with respect to the transmission axis of the polarizer, a quarter wave
 plate with its fast axis at an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 with respect to the fast axis of the transparency, and an analyzer with
 its transmission axis at an angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta$
\end_inset

 with respect to the fast axis of the quarter wave plate.
 The angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 have to be chosen such that the transmission of the compound optical system
 is zero.
 This gives the matrix equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(R(-\theta-\psi-\vartheta)\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]R(\theta+\psi+\vartheta)\right)\left(R(-\theta-\psi)\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & i
\end{array}\right]R(\theta+\psi)\right)\nonumber \\
\left(R(-\theta)\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & e^{i\phi}
\end{array}\right]R(\theta)\right)\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1
\end{array}\right] & = & \left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the rotation matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(\alpha)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\alpha & \sin\alpha\\
-\sin\alpha & \cos\alpha
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A very lengthy application of matrix and trigonometric algebra leads to
 the relationship
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tan\phi=-\frac{\tan2\vartheta}{\sin2\psi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is independent of the transparency angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

