\begin_layout Standard
We measured the intensity as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{a}$
\end_inset

, for two different values of the angle of the polarizer 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{\circ}\pm1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $30^{\circ}\pm1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 The experiment was particularly complicated given that the intensity of
 the transmitted beam fluctuated considerably over variable periods of time
 between a minimum and maximum value once a polarizer was put in front of
 it.
 We attempted to measure the values at the maxima and minima of each fluctuation
 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{a}$
\end_inset

, but we decided not to use the measured value of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 since the amplitude of the fluctuations was too large for the case of a
 single polarizer, and because this amplitude varied as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, we fit a model given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I(I_{0},\,\theta_{p},\,\theta_{a},\,I_{min})=I_{0}\cos^{2}(\theta_{p}-\theta_{a}+\phi)+I_{min}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and plot both the minimum and maximum values of the intensity as a function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\theta=\theta_{p}-\theta_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 gives us the location of the eigenstates of the analyzer, and allows us
 to obtain the relationship between the angle measured by the rotation stages
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\theta$
\end_inset

 and the real angle between the transmission axes of the polarizers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\theta_{real}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\theta=\Delta\theta_{real}-\phi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figures 1 and 2 show the results for the cases when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{p}=0\pm1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{p}=30\pm1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 The best value for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{o}$
\end_inset

 was found to be 
\begin_inset Formula $4.91\pm0.13\,V$
\end_inset

, by averaging the best values for obtained for each of the two cases.
 Similarly, the best fit value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=9.4\pm1.1^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
 It was not possible to recover an accurate value for the extinction ratio
 due to the fact that the intensity at the minima was less than the intensity
 of the ambient light, and as such the errors involved in the calculations
 became too big.
 For instance, we measured the intensity of the background lights in the
 room to be 
\begin_inset Formula $15\pm5\,mV$
\end_inset

, and the values recorded by the voltmeter close to the minima were ~20
 mV, which included the contribution of the ambient lights.
 In fact, the optimal fits for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{min}$
\end_inset

 were negative in both cases, and the magnitude of the average error for
 the extinction ratio ended up being 7000% greater than the magnitude of
 its nominal value.
