 This is consistent with the values found, with the nominal value within
 4% of the value given by the manufacturer of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1.517$
\end_inset

 (as given in [6]), and almost within the error bars.
 However, this measurement of the refraction index is not as accurate as
 those performed in the previous project, where the discrepancies were never
 greater than 2%, and were as low as 0.2%.
 The reason for this likely resides in the alignment of the reflecting interface
 of the prism with respect to the incident light.
 This was done by having the light reflected from the prism in the initial
 position to go back into the laser aperture.
 However, even a very small angle of deviation from perfect alignment gives
 rise to significant errors.
 For instance, if this misalignment was on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5^{\circ}$
\end_inset

